				    Adamson, June.   1997.  &ldquo;The SED in Oak Ridge,  1943-1946: Using a Secret Newsletter by a Secret Army detachment to Learn More  About a Secret City in Tennessee&rdquo; [Secret Engineering Detachment].  <em>Tennessee Historical Quarterly</em> 56  (Fall): 196-211.</p>
                  <p align="left">Anderson, Robert E.   2007.  <em>One of Lincoln&rsquo;s Best</em> [General Joseph A. J. Lightburn, 1824-1901].   Morgantown, W.Va.: R.E. Anderson.   87 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Athey, Lou.  1996.  &quot;Loyalty and Civil Liberty in Fayette  County During the Civil War.&quot;  <em>West  Virginia History</em> 55 (1996): 1-24.</p>
                  <p align="left">Ayers, Edward L.   2003.  <em>In the Presence of Mine  Enemies: War in the Heart of America, 1859-1863</em> [Franklin Co., Pa.; Augusta  Co., Va.].  New York: W.W. Norton.  472 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Ayers, Edward L., Gary W. Gallagher, and Andrew J. Torget,  eds.  2006.  <em>Crucible of the Civil War: Virginia from  Secession to Commemoration</em> [W.Va.; Va. group identity; shaded county  outline maps].  Charlottesville:  University of Virginia Press.  226 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Baggett, James Alex.  2009.  <em>Homegrown Yankees: Tennessee&rsquo;s Union  Cavalry in the Civil War</em> [most East Tennesseans].  Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University  Press.  444 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Ballard, Sandra L., and Leila E. Weinstein, eds.  2007.  <em>Neighbor  to Neighbor: A Memoir of Family, Community, and Civil War in Appalachian North  Carolina</em> [Ashe Co.; William Albert Wilson, 1861-1951; essays by Patricia D.  Beaver, Martin Crawford, John C. Inscoe].   Boone, N.C.: Center for Appalachian Studies, Appalachian State  University.  180 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Barbour, Russ.   2003.  &ldquo;Major General Charles R.  Fox&rdquo; [profile of highly decorated veteran; b. 1912].  <em>Goldenseal: West Virginia Traditional Life</em> 29 (Summer): 10-17.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bard, David.  2004.  <em>Civil War in the New River Valley  1861-1865: 3 One-Day Driving Tours</em> [W.Va.-Va.; guidebook, 43 maps,  chronology].  Charleston, W.Va.: Quarrier  Press.  144 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Barksdale, Kevin T.   2004.  &ldquo;&lsquo;Beneath the Golden  Stairs&rsquo;: Gender, Unionization, and Mobilization in World War II West Virginia&rdquo;  [Glendale; Marx Toy Workers Union].  <em>Ohio  Valley History</em> 4 (Spring): 21-42.</p>
                  <p align="left">Barnes, Kenneth C.   2001.  &ldquo;The Williams Clan&rsquo;s Civil  War: How an Arkansas Farm Family Became a Guerrilla Band.&rdquo;  In <em>Enemies of the Country: New  Perspectives on Unionists in the Civil War South</em>, eds. J. Inscoe and R.  Kenzer, 188-207.  Athens: University of  Georgia Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Beaver, Patricia D.   2007.  &ldquo;The Civil War on the North  Fork of the New River: Sustaining Community.&rdquo;   In <em>Neighbor to Neighbor: A Memoir of Family, Community, and Civil War  in Appalachian North Carolina</em> [Ashe Co.], eds. S. Ballard and L. Weinstein,  20-36.  Boone, N.C.: Center for  Appalachian Studies, Appalachian State University.</p>
                  <p align="left">Berkey, Jonathan M.   2001.  &ldquo;Fighting the Devil with  Fire: David Hunter Strother&rsquo;s Private Civil War.&rdquo;  In <em>Enemies of the Country: New  Perspectives on Unionists in the Civil War South</em>, eds. J. Inscoe and R.  Kenzer, 18-36.  Athens: University of  Georgia Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bertsch, Friedrich, and Wilhelm Stängel.  2010.  <em>A  German Hurrah! Civil War Letters of Friedrich Bertsch and Wilhelm Stängel, 9th  Ohio Infantry</em>.  Translated and edited  by Joseph R. Reinhart.  Kent, Ohio: Kent  State University Press.  370 pp.  Camp life, political and social observations;  campaigns in western Va., Ky., and parts of Tenn., Ala. and Miss.</p>
                  <p align="left">Billinger, Robert D.   2008.  <em>Nazi POWs in the Tar  Heel State</em>.  Gainesville: University  Press of Florida.  246 pp.  Five permanent  N.C. camps, 13 branch camps, 10,000 POWs.</p>
                  <p align="left">Birdwell, Michael E.   2003.  &ldquo;Old Hickory and the  Hindenburg Line: The 30th Division in World War I.&rdquo;  <em>Journal of East Tennessee History</em> 74  (2002): 1-32.</p>
                  <p align="left">Birdwell, Michael E.   2004.  &ldquo;Gobble Like a Turkey:  Alvin C. York and American Popular Culture&rdquo; [immortalized WWI Tenn. hero].  In <em>Rural Life and Culture in the Upper  Cumberland</em>, eds. M. Birdwell and W. Dickinson, 159-177.  Lexington: University Press of Kentucky.</p>
                  <p align="left">Black, Robert C., with a new foreword by Gary W.  Gallagher.  1998 [1952].  <em>The Railroads of the Confederacy</em>.  Reprint.   Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press.  360 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bohannon, Keith S.  2001.  &ldquo;They Had Determined to Root Us Out: Dual  Memoirs by a Unionist Couple in Blue Ridge Georgia.&rdquo;  In <em>Enemies of the Country: New  Perspectives on Unionists in the Civil War South</em>, eds. J. Inscoe and R.  Kenzer, 97-120.  Athens: University of  Georgia Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bollier, Sam.   2009.  &ldquo;&lsquo;Our Own Paradise  Invaded&rsquo;: Imagining Civil War-Era East Tennessee&rdquo; [outside and Northern  perceptions, and self-perceptions].  <em>Tennessee  Historical Quarterly</em> 68, no. 3 (Winter): 391-410.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bonnstetter, Cathy Meo.   2001.  &ldquo;&lsquo;You Never Forget&rsquo;: Taylor  County&rsquo;s Color Guard&rdquo; [VFW Post 3081].  <em>Goldenseal:  West Virginia Traditional Life</em> 27 (Winter): 9-13.</p>
                  <p align="left">Booth, George Wilson.   2000 [1898].  <em>A Maryland Boy in  Lee&rsquo;s Army: Personal Reminiscences of a Maryland Soldier in the War Between the  States, 1861-1865</em> [Shenandoah Valley campaigns; Va., W.Va.].  Reprint.   Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press.   184 pp.  Originally published:  Baltimore: privately published.</p>
                  <p align="left">Boynton, Henry V.   2010.  <em>The Battles of  Chickamauga and Chattanooga and the Organizations Engaged</em> [1863].  Edited with a new introduction by Timothy B.  Smith.   Knoxville: University of  Tennessee Press.  This volume combines  Boynton&rsquo;s [1835-1905] three short books, <em>The Battle of Chickamauga, Georgia</em>; <em>Battles about Chattanooga, Tennessee</em>; and <em>The Campaign for  Chattanooga</em>.</p>
                  <p align="left">Bragg, Rick.  2003.   <em>I Am a Soldier, Too: The Jessica Lynch  Story</em> [Iraq War, 2003; prisoner of war; W.Va. native, b. 1983].  New York: Knopf.  207 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Brooks, Jason.   1997.  &ldquo;No Law In ... The Civil  War in the New River Valley&rdquo; [Va., W.Va.].   In <em>Proceedings, New River Symposium, April 11-12, 1997, Glade Springs  Resort, Daniels, West Virginia, 1-10.   Glen Jean, W.Va.: </em>National Park Service<em>.</em></p>
                  <p align="left">Bryan, Charles F.   2004.  &ldquo;&lsquo;Tories&rsquo; Amidst Rebels:  Confederate Occupation of East Tennessee, 1861-63.&rdquo;  <em>Journal of East Tennessee History</em> 75  (2003): 43-61.</p>
                  <p align="left">Burns, G. Frank, Kelly Sergio, and Rex Bennett.  2004.   &ldquo;Somewhere in Tennessee: The Cumberland Wartime, 1940-1947&rdquo; [Camp  Forrest; war games, 21-county area].  In <em>Rural  Life and Culture in the Upper Cumberland</em>, eds. M. Birdwell and W.  Dickinson, 227-245.  Lexington:  University Press of Kentucky.</p>
                  <p align="left">Butko, Brian, and Nicholas P. Ciotola, eds.  2003.  <em>Industry  and Infantry: The Civil War in Western Pennsylvania</em> [collection of eight  articles].  Pittsburgh: Historical  Society of Western Pennsylvania.  126 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Caleo, Robert L.   2007.  &ldquo;&lsquo;A Most Serious Wound&rsquo;:  The Memorial of George Farragut.&rdquo;  <em>Journal  of East Tennessee History</em> 79: 63-79.</p>
                  <p align="left">Carmichael, Peter S.   2003.  &ldquo;So Far From God and So  Close to Stonewall Jackson: The Executions of Three Shenandoah Valley  Soldiers.&rdquo;  <em>Virginia Magazine of  History and Biography</em> 111 (no. 1): 33-66.</p>
                  <p align="left">Chapman, Reid, and Deborah Miles.  2006.  <em>Asheville  and Western North Carolina in World War II</em> [photo-retrospective].  Images of America.  Charleston, S.C.: Arcadia.  127 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Chronology of Major Events in Appalachia&rsquo;s Civil War.  1997.   In <em>The Civil War in Appalachia: Collected Essays</em>, eds. K. Noe and  S. Wilson, xxxv-xxxvii.  Knoxville:  University of Tennessee Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Cohen, Stan.  2003  [1990].  <em>A Pictorial Guide to West  Virginia&rsquo;s Civil War Sites and Related Information</em>.  Charleston, W.Va: Quarrier Press.  120 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Collins, Darrell L.    2007.  <em>The Jones-Imboden Raid:  The Confederate Attempt to Destroy the Baltimore &amp; Ohio Railroad and Retake  West Virginia</em>.  Jefferson, N.C.:  McFarland.  217 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Cooling, B. Franklin.   1999.  &ldquo;A People&rsquo;s War: Partisan  Conflict in Tennessee and Kentucky.&rdquo;  In <em>Guerrillas,  Unionists, and Violence on the Confederate Home Front</em>, ed. D. Sutherland,  113-132.  Fayetteville: University of  Arkansas Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Cooling, Benjamin Franklin.   1997.  <em>Fort Donelson&rsquo;s Legacy:  War and Society in Tennessee and Kentucky, 1862-1863.</em>  Knoxville: University of Tennessee  Press.  420 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Cordes, Kathleen Ann.   1999.  &ldquo;Overmountain Victory  National Historic Trail.&rdquo;  In <em>America&rsquo;s  National Historic Trails</em> [guidebook], by K. Cordes, 40-63.  Norman: University of Oklahoma Press.</p>
                  <p align="left">Cozzens, Peter.   2008.  <em>Shenandoah 1862:  Stonewall Jackson&rsquo;s Valley Campaign</em>.   Chapel Hill: University of North Carolina Press.  623 pp.</p>
                  <p align="left">Craig, Tom Moore, ed.   2009.  <em>Upcountry South Carolina  Goes to War: Letters of the Anderson, Brockman, and Moore Families, 1853-1865</em> [Spartanburg Co.].  Introduction by Tom  Moore Craig, and Melissa Walker.   Columbia: University of South Carolina Press.  190 pp.</p>
